<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900629-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>900629-0030.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- BASF AG:   West German Firm Says   First-Half Sales Declined</HL><DATE>06/29/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   G.BAS</CO><LP>   BASF AG, a West German chemical company, said itsworld-wide first-half sales decreased an indicated 4% from ayear earlier to 23.6 billion marks ($14.18 billion), markingthe first decline for that period since 1987, when sales fell6%.   In the 1989 first half, BASF sales rose 13% to 24.46billion marks.</LP><TEXT>   BASF and other West German chemical makers' earnings andsales have been hurt this year by the negative effect of thestrong mark against other currencies. Some of the company'sproduct sectors also have been under downward price pressurebecause of fierce market competition. BASF's first-quartersales were little changed at 11.89 billion marks, comparedwith a year earlier, but pretax profit slid 6.6% to 845million marks.   Chairman Hans Albers, in prepared remarks for the annualmeeting, nonetheless reiterated he is confident BASF willcome close to matching last year's earnings. In 1989, BASFprofit rose 43% to 2.02 billion marks from 1988, and pretaxprofit was up 18% at 4.39 billion marks.</TEXT></DOC>